1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,620
 Have a seat.

2
00:00:02,620 --> 00:00:03,620
 Welcome to the Vine.

3
00:00:03,620 --> 00:00:05,100
 We're so glad you're here.

4
00:00:05,100 --> 00:00:06,960
 My name's Andrew, one of the pastors here.

5
00:00:06,960 --> 00:00:11,760
 And it's a beautiful thing that we get to gather in Hong Kong and worship Jesus.

6
00:00:11,760 --> 00:00:12,860
 Amen.

7
00:00:12,860 --> 00:00:19,900
 And what a joy, what a joy it is to be alive in this time of history, in this time of what

8
00:00:19,900 --> 00:00:21,860
 the Spirit is doing around the world.

9
00:00:21,860 --> 00:00:27,960
 And, you know, there really is a sense of the church growing, Christianity becoming

10
00:00:27,960 --> 00:00:33,680
 something that people want to be engaging with, the joy of seeing revival in certain

11
00:00:33,680 --> 00:00:35,640
 parts of the world at the moment.

12
00:00:35,640 --> 00:00:40,520
 And what a beautiful thing it is that God's called us to this city, to these people, to

13
00:00:40,520 --> 00:00:45,720
 this community, this society, to live the life of Christ so publicly and openly.

14
00:00:45,720 --> 00:00:47,560
 Isn't that great?

15
00:00:47,560 --> 00:00:52,880
 I want to start today by just confessing something to you.

16
00:00:52,880 --> 00:00:57,680
 The topic that I want to talk about today is one where over the last 20 years of my

17
00:00:57,680 --> 00:01:02,200
 ministry I've actually avoided speaking about.

18
00:01:02,200 --> 00:01:08,440
 Now when a preacher avoids speaking about a topic, it's usually for one of two reasons.

19
00:01:08,440 --> 00:01:12,480
 First of all, it might be because maybe the topic is super controversial or it's super

20
00:01:12,480 --> 00:01:17,040
 pastorally sensitive for that particular community and what's going on, and it wouldn't just

21
00:01:17,040 --> 00:01:18,400
 be right to talk about it.

22
00:01:18,400 --> 00:01:22,040
 So maybe we put it aside and come back to it at a different time.

23
00:01:22,040 --> 00:01:27,120
 Or secondly, the reason why preachers don't preach on a particular topic is usually because

24
00:01:27,120 --> 00:01:31,640
 we realize as preachers that if we were to preach on that topic, it would require a lot

25
00:01:31,640 --> 00:01:34,880
 of work within ourselves first of all.

26
00:01:34,880 --> 00:01:39,840
 We realize that that topic opens up for us a lot of pain, a lot of things that we're

27
00:01:39,840 --> 00:01:45,600
 wrestling with, a lot of things that we know we need to deal with, that if we talked about

28
00:01:45,600 --> 00:01:49,640
 that topic openly with the church, we would have to confess some things.

29
00:01:49,640 --> 00:01:50,840
 We'd have to be pretty open about it.

30
00:01:50,840 --> 00:01:52,240
 We'd have to be pretty transparent.

31
00:01:52,240 --> 00:01:56,960
 We'd probably need to let the Holy Spirit into that darker places of our lives.

32
00:01:56,960 --> 00:02:00,240
 And we'd rather not actually have everybody know about all the brokenness and the sin

33
00:02:00,240 --> 00:02:01,280
 that's within us.

34
00:02:01,280 --> 00:02:03,200
 And so we basically talk about other topics.

35
00:02:03,200 --> 00:02:05,400
 And to be honest, nobody's going to really want to talk about that topic anyway.

36
00:02:05,400 --> 00:02:06,400
 It's a boring topic.

37
00:02:06,400 --> 00:02:07,680
 Why would you want to ever talk about a topic like that?

38
00:02:07,680 --> 00:02:08,680
 That's a scrap.

39
00:02:08,680 --> 00:02:09,680
 We're just going to talk about other things.

40
00:02:09,680 --> 00:02:10,920
 There's nobody who knows that I'm struggling with that.

41
00:02:10,920 --> 00:02:11,920
 And that's good.

42
00:02:11,920 --> 00:02:12,920
 I would rather keep it that way.

43
00:02:12,920 --> 00:02:14,200
 Are you with me?

44
00:02:14,200 --> 00:02:18,080
 I wonder if you could work out which of those two is the reason why I've never spoken on

45
00:02:18,080 --> 00:02:22,640
 this particular topic for 20 years.

46
00:02:22,640 --> 00:02:30,240
 I want to talk this morning on the topic of ambition, which ironically has never been

47
00:02:30,240 --> 00:02:35,440
 an ambition of mine.

48
00:02:35,440 --> 00:02:40,040
 Most scholars would define ambition in this particular way.

49
00:02:40,040 --> 00:02:45,240
 They would say it's a strong desire to do or to achieve something, typically requiring

50
00:02:45,240 --> 00:02:52,240
 determination, hard work, and at times, prioritize self-focus and personal advancement.

51
00:02:52,240 --> 00:02:58,000
 I stand before you today to tell you that for about 30 years of my adult life, so from

52
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:04,080
 the age of about 20 years old to my age now, don't work out how old I am, I have deeply

53
00:03:04,080 --> 00:03:09,720
 struggled with the reality that I'm an incredibly driven individual.

54
00:03:09,720 --> 00:03:13,440
 I have huge amounts of what's on the screen back there.

55
00:03:13,440 --> 00:03:14,960
 I am driven.

56
00:03:14,960 --> 00:03:16,920
 I am ambitious.

57
00:03:16,920 --> 00:03:19,720
 I am motivated by achievements.

58
00:03:19,720 --> 00:03:22,160
 I want people to see me.

59
00:03:22,160 --> 00:03:25,080
 I like to be recognized, to be known.

60
00:03:25,080 --> 00:03:31,200
 I like to achieve a goal, set a high goal, and work really hard and achieve that goal

61
00:03:31,200 --> 00:03:35,720
 because that makes me feel great.

62
00:03:35,720 --> 00:03:40,800
 And the reality is that all the personality profile testing that I've done over the last

63
00:03:40,800 --> 00:03:43,360
 30 years of my life, it always pretty much said the same thing.

64
00:03:43,360 --> 00:03:47,840
 Andrew is an incredibly driven individual who loves to be motivated by set goals and

65
00:03:47,840 --> 00:03:54,160
 achieving those goals and, and this is a direct quote, he has the competitive drive of an

66
00:03:54,160 --> 00:04:03,440
 Olympic athlete coupled with the self-focus of a narcissistic loner.

67
00:04:03,440 --> 00:04:04,440
 That's your pastor.

68
00:04:04,440 --> 00:04:05,440
 Yes.

69
00:04:05,440 --> 00:04:08,840
 There are lots of other great churches in Hong Kong, by the way, if you would like to

70
00:04:08,840 --> 00:04:13,440
 now go to those.

71
00:04:13,440 --> 00:04:18,880
 But I recognize that on one side of me, there's this drive within me to achieve, to do something,

72
00:04:18,880 --> 00:04:21,000
 to make a name for myself.

73
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:24,560
 And I've recognized over the years that that drive within me is so strong that it's driven

74
00:04:24,560 --> 00:04:30,120
 me to the point of burnout at times, being overwhelmed, to hurting other people around

75
00:04:30,120 --> 00:04:35,460
 me as perhaps I've pushed others down while I've tried to raise myself up.

76
00:04:35,460 --> 00:04:40,240
 But on the other side, I love Jesus.

77
00:04:40,240 --> 00:04:45,680
 And I have these other things inside of me that speak of, of wanting to serve others

78
00:04:45,680 --> 00:04:51,400
 and a deep call in my life to be a pastor who gives his life on behalf of the people

79
00:04:51,400 --> 00:04:53,040
 of a community.

80
00:04:53,040 --> 00:04:58,400
 And I recognize that I have these two things at work within my soul and my spirit, almost

81
00:04:58,400 --> 00:05:03,600
 at all times warring against each other.

82
00:05:03,600 --> 00:05:09,660
 This drive to prove myself and to be someone in the world and this beautiful idea that

83
00:05:09,660 --> 00:05:13,300
 I should lay down my life for Christ.

84
00:05:13,300 --> 00:05:21,680
 And I realized that I had this contrast within me where I love Jesus, but I also more often

85
00:05:21,680 --> 00:05:27,040
 than not love myself more.

86
00:05:27,040 --> 00:05:34,020
 If I was to be really honest with you, I would say this, personal gain and death to self

87
00:05:34,020 --> 00:05:39,740
 are terrible mixes.

88
00:05:39,740 --> 00:05:43,380
 I wonder if that resonates a little bit with you as well.

89
00:05:43,380 --> 00:05:44,800
 We live here in Hong Kong, don't we?

90
00:05:44,800 --> 00:05:50,000
 One of the most driven cities in the world where we're raised from a young age to be

91
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:56,480
 achievers, where we work hard, we struggle well, we push ourselves, we want to get that

92
00:05:56,480 --> 00:05:58,980
 great job and work for that great company.

93
00:05:58,980 --> 00:06:03,860
 Having gone to a great university, we have this internal drive that seems to push us

94
00:06:03,860 --> 00:06:08,860
 at all times to make a name for ourselves and to be something in this world.

95
00:06:08,860 --> 00:06:11,280
 I think all of us can recognize that.

96
00:06:11,280 --> 00:06:15,800
 And to be honest with you, in and of itself, is it really that bad?

97
00:06:15,800 --> 00:06:19,880
 I mean, it's good, isn't it, as human beings to want to achieve something in this world,

98
00:06:19,880 --> 00:06:24,360
 to want to actually produce and do something with our lives?

99
00:06:24,360 --> 00:06:29,120
 Isn't it a healthy thing to have a purpose and to want to have value and meaning and

100
00:06:29,120 --> 00:06:32,600
 to do something positive in the community around you?

101
00:06:32,600 --> 00:06:37,720
 I mean, actually, go back to Genesis chapter one and two, this beautiful creation of humanity

102
00:06:37,720 --> 00:06:39,040
 made in the image of God.

103
00:06:39,040 --> 00:06:40,760
 And what does God do?

104
00:06:40,760 --> 00:06:44,040
 God gives humanity ambition.

105
00:06:44,040 --> 00:06:49,360
 God says to humanity, "Go into my creation and steward it well.

106
00:06:49,360 --> 00:06:51,000
 Help it to flourish.

107
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:53,960
 Bring life to the things that I've created around you."

108
00:06:53,960 --> 00:06:59,040
 So inherent into what it means to be created in the image of God as human beings is this

109
00:06:59,040 --> 00:07:02,240
 beautiful thought that I want my life to count.

110
00:07:02,240 --> 00:07:03,560
 I want it to matter.

111
00:07:03,560 --> 00:07:08,360
 I want to impact the world for good.

112
00:07:08,360 --> 00:07:12,680
 But then we become a Christian and we come into this relationship with Jesus.

113
00:07:12,680 --> 00:07:18,480
 And then suddenly other ideas begin to be made known to us and we begin to wrestle with

114
00:07:18,480 --> 00:07:27,040
 important ideas like meekness and weakness, like the laying down of my life, like the

115
00:07:27,040 --> 00:07:33,800
 idea of death and resurrection, the idea of crucifixion of self, the idea that I need

116
00:07:33,800 --> 00:07:38,120
 to be born again and made into a new being.

117
00:07:38,120 --> 00:07:44,040
 And as Christians, maybe we could be forgiven for thinking that is it irreconcilable to

118
00:07:44,040 --> 00:07:49,680
 actually be somebody who achieves something in the world and also a Christ follower?

119
00:07:49,680 --> 00:07:54,560
 Can those two things actually sit together in some way?

120
00:07:54,560 --> 00:07:59,440
 And I think that when churches ignore this issue, when they don't talk about ambition,

121
00:07:59,440 --> 00:08:03,600
 when they don't recognize the brokenness within it, but also the redemption that could be

122
00:08:03,600 --> 00:08:08,360
 there as well, I think one of two things can happen in a church.

123
00:08:08,360 --> 00:08:13,560
 One is that highly successful people in the world's eyes come into church and they come

124
00:08:13,560 --> 00:08:17,360
 in because they're eager to discover there's more to life and they want to connect with

125
00:08:17,360 --> 00:08:23,720
 Jesus and they come into a church and they find a community that judges them, that makes

126
00:08:23,720 --> 00:08:30,000
 them feel bad because they've been successful in the world's eyes, makes them feel bad that

127
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:34,000
 they've achieved something, gained something, worked well, gotten some money, whatever it

128
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:35,000
 might be.

129
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:38,680
 And it suddenly feels for that community that everybody else is judging them because they're

130
00:08:38,680 --> 00:08:41,920
 not as spiritual as them.

131
00:08:41,920 --> 00:08:44,640
 And those people leave the church.

132
00:08:44,640 --> 00:08:49,800
 Or perhaps a successful person has come into the church and has given their life to Jesus

133
00:08:49,800 --> 00:08:52,940
 and has found something new and fresh and alive.

134
00:08:52,940 --> 00:08:57,160
 And suddenly it's like, "Oh my gosh, I've been doing all this stuff and I've achieved

135
00:08:57,160 --> 00:08:58,760
 and I've been doing all these things."

136
00:08:58,760 --> 00:09:02,960
 Ironically, perhaps things that actually the Holy Spirit has anointed them to do, but now

137
00:09:02,960 --> 00:09:06,360
 that they're a Christian, they think that is not Christian enough.

138
00:09:06,360 --> 00:09:11,560
 And they feel like they need to give away and quit that job or do whatever, because

139
00:09:11,560 --> 00:09:17,320
 that doesn't seem to be Christian enough now that they've found Jesus.

140
00:09:17,320 --> 00:09:21,000
 Which is interesting because William Wilberforce, one of my heroes, one of the great social

141
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:26,020
 reformers of the 18th century, he wrestled with this very issue.

142
00:09:26,020 --> 00:09:29,480
 God had raised him up to a prominent place in the public sphere.

143
00:09:29,480 --> 00:09:34,040
 He was working within parliament to try to kind of bring the abolishment of slavery in

144
00:09:34,040 --> 00:09:35,880
 the British empire.

145
00:09:35,880 --> 00:09:40,800
 But right before he achieved that goal, he was super driven by that goal, working hard

146
00:09:40,800 --> 00:09:41,960
 in the public square.

147
00:09:41,960 --> 00:09:47,240
 He was a Christian wrestling with this internal battle within him, thinking that maybe he

148
00:09:47,240 --> 00:09:50,520
 should become a parish priest.

149
00:09:50,520 --> 00:09:54,920
 And this drive of, "I have this ambition to do something in the world, in the public

150
00:09:54,920 --> 00:10:00,920
 sphere, but yet maybe I should have the quiet life of a priest," was warring away at him.

151
00:10:00,920 --> 00:10:04,760
 And a friend came to him and said, "You've got to understand, William, that it's just

152
00:10:04,760 --> 00:10:11,840
 as noble to do what you're doing in the public space as it would be to be a priest."

153
00:10:11,840 --> 00:10:13,400
 And Wilberforce had to wrestle with that.

154
00:10:13,400 --> 00:10:16,720
 And he comes out of it and he goes, "Okay, I'm going to commit to this."

155
00:10:16,720 --> 00:10:21,960
 And just a few years later in 1807, they passed the law in parliament to abolish slavery in

156
00:10:21,960 --> 00:10:26,200
 the whole of the British empire.

157
00:10:26,200 --> 00:10:32,600
 The reality is there is a tension between ambition and following Jesus.

158
00:10:32,600 --> 00:10:38,360
 And if it is true that Jesus says we are to be salt and light in the world, then surely

159
00:10:38,360 --> 00:10:44,960
 our flourishing in the very place that God has planted us right now is not inherently

160
00:10:44,960 --> 00:10:45,960
 wrong.

161
00:10:45,960 --> 00:10:46,960
 Does that make sense?

162
00:10:46,960 --> 00:10:51,640
 So there's got to be something about where God has planted me right now, whether it's

163
00:10:51,640 --> 00:10:55,360
 business, whether it's entertainment, whether it's education, whether it's your family,

164
00:10:55,360 --> 00:10:57,160
 whatever it might be in your home.

165
00:10:57,160 --> 00:11:00,160
 But wherever God has planted you right now, if we're to be salt and light, surely our

166
00:11:00,160 --> 00:11:05,640
 flourishing, our desire to do well, our desire to do a difference and make a difference in

167
00:11:05,640 --> 00:11:08,480
 our lives, that cannot inherently be wrong.

168
00:11:08,480 --> 00:11:11,860
 But there is this tension.

169
00:11:11,860 --> 00:11:12,920
 Maybe I could ask it another way.

170
00:11:12,920 --> 00:11:15,360
 Let me ask it as a question.

171
00:11:15,360 --> 00:11:24,760
 Is it possible for a Christian to redefine ambition in such a way that actually it becomes

172
00:11:24,760 --> 00:11:30,680
 one of the most powerful tools we have to reveal the gospel?

173
00:11:30,680 --> 00:11:32,360
 Come on church.

174
00:11:32,360 --> 00:11:38,200
 Could our ambition be so redefined within us that the way in which we achieve, the way

175
00:11:38,200 --> 00:11:43,040
 in which we succeed, the way in which we drive for something good in this world might be

176
00:11:43,040 --> 00:11:49,600
 the most powerful way that we reveal the person of Jesus to our workplaces, to our places

177
00:11:49,600 --> 00:11:51,900
 of education, to our families.

178
00:11:51,900 --> 00:11:59,760
 Could it be that public faith could be dramatically impacted through our ambition?

179
00:11:59,760 --> 00:12:03,160
 I want to offer an answer to that question in our time together this morning by looking

180
00:12:03,160 --> 00:12:06,500
 at the life of Paul, the apostle Paul.

181
00:12:06,500 --> 00:12:11,940
 But particularly I want to contrast his life before he met Jesus when he was known as Saul,

182
00:12:11,940 --> 00:12:15,940
 his Jewish name, and then his life after he met Jesus as Paul.

183
00:12:15,940 --> 00:12:20,180
 And I want to pull out a couple of things in this contrast to you to help you to see

184
00:12:20,180 --> 00:12:24,500
 the journey of ambition that Paul went through.

185
00:12:24,500 --> 00:12:30,140
 Paul himself was an incredibly driven individual when he was called Saul.

186
00:12:30,140 --> 00:12:33,900
 Saul was his Hebrew name, his birth name, and he was incredibly driven.

187
00:12:33,900 --> 00:12:38,220
 In fact, when we are introduced to him in the New Testament, we see a man filled with

188
00:12:38,220 --> 00:12:44,220
 passion, a man filled with zeal, a man filled with ambition, who is singularly focused on

189
00:12:44,220 --> 00:12:47,140
 one primary goal, and he was very good at this goal.

190
00:12:47,140 --> 00:12:52,080
 And that was trying to eradicate this growing sect that was following Jesus.

191
00:12:52,080 --> 00:12:55,700
 In fact, later on in the church in Philippi, he writes to the church in Philippi, and he

192
00:12:55,700 --> 00:12:58,740
 says this about himself in the days of Saul.

193
00:12:58,740 --> 00:13:02,100
 He said, "If anyone else thinks that they have reason to be confident in the flesh,

194
00:13:02,100 --> 00:13:04,140
 oh, I have more."

195
00:13:04,140 --> 00:13:10,300
 He says, "Circumcised on the eighth day of the people of Israel, of the tribe of Benjamin,

196
00:13:10,300 --> 00:13:16,420
 a Hebrew of Hebrews, in regards to the law of Pharisee, as for zeal, persecuting the

197
00:13:16,420 --> 00:13:20,740
 church, as for legalistic righteousness, faultless."

198
00:13:20,740 --> 00:13:27,140
 This is like Paul unveiling his resume, and if you were parents of a daughter in Hong

199
00:13:27,140 --> 00:13:29,780
 Kong, you'd be like, "Sign me up.

200
00:13:29,780 --> 00:13:32,460
 I want my daughter to marry this guy."

201
00:13:32,460 --> 00:13:33,460
 He's the best.

202
00:13:33,460 --> 00:13:34,460
 He's a Hebrew of Hebrews.

203
00:13:34,460 --> 00:13:35,800
 He's from the tribe of Benjamin.

204
00:13:35,800 --> 00:13:38,860
 He was faultless in his legalistic zeal.

205
00:13:38,860 --> 00:13:44,300
 And then he says this, "My zeal," another way of translating that word, "My ambition

206
00:13:44,300 --> 00:13:48,620
 is the persecution of the church."

207
00:13:48,620 --> 00:13:53,940
 And when we're first introduced to Saul in the book of Acts, this is exactly what he's

208
00:13:53,940 --> 00:13:55,180
 about to do.

209
00:13:55,180 --> 00:13:59,220
 He's about to go to the town of Damascus to persecute the church there, and when you read

210
00:13:59,220 --> 00:14:05,420
 it, you get this sense of the drive and the selfish ambition that's working inside of

211
00:14:05,420 --> 00:14:11,780
 him to achieve a goal that, interestingly, he thought was God-ordained, but was exactly

212
00:14:11,780 --> 00:14:13,780
 the opposite.

213
00:14:13,780 --> 00:14:16,820
 Let me show you this from Acts 9, starting in verse 1.

214
00:14:16,820 --> 00:14:22,260
 "Meanwhile, Saul was still breathing out murderous threats against the Lord's disciples.

215
00:14:22,260 --> 00:14:27,020
 He went to the high priests and asked him for letters to the synagogues in Damascus,

216
00:14:27,020 --> 00:14:31,220
 so that if he found anyone there who belonged to the way, whether men or women, he might

217
00:14:31,220 --> 00:14:33,780
 take them as prisoners to Jerusalem."

218
00:14:33,780 --> 00:14:34,940
 Let's just stop there.

219
00:14:34,940 --> 00:14:40,780
 So here's Saul, the ambitious, self-driven, 100% focused in eradicating the church.

220
00:14:40,780 --> 00:14:45,180
 He goes to the high priest and he says, "Give me letters, commendation, so that it would

221
00:14:45,180 --> 00:14:49,380
 empower me, give me more power to go to the synagogues in Damascus.

222
00:14:49,380 --> 00:14:53,060
 I'm going to round up all these nasty Christians, and I'm going to bring them back to Jerusalem."

223
00:14:53,060 --> 00:15:01,740
 Us, high achievers, we love power that comes from getting accolades, from getting diplomas,

224
00:15:01,740 --> 00:15:05,740
 from getting titles, from getting whatever it is, degrees, not that any of that is bad

225
00:15:05,740 --> 00:15:12,100
 in and of itself, but oftentimes, sort of these high driven, selfish, ambitious people

226
00:15:12,100 --> 00:15:17,460
 collect those things to gain power, to be able to push that power over someone else.

227
00:15:17,460 --> 00:15:18,620
 You're following this?

228
00:15:18,620 --> 00:15:23,420
 So here you've got Saul, who's accumulating all of this stuff to ensure that he's even

229
00:15:23,420 --> 00:15:27,180
 more powerful, so he can achieve these selfish gains.

